<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1922-02-02T19:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1922-02-02T19:00:00-05:00" n="26" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d26">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">500.A4a/5: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of
                                        State</gloss> to the Minister in Siam</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Brodie</hi></persName>)</head>
                            <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1922-02-02T19:00:00-05:00"><hi rend="italic">February
                                            2, 1922—7 p.m.</hi></date></dateline></opener>
                            <p>7. You may informally advise the Minister for Foreign Affairs that
                                the Secretary of State is gratified to learn the sentiments
                                expressed in first paragraph of your number I January 7, 2 p.m.</p>
                            <p>You should explain to the Minister for Foreign Affairs that the
                                Four-Power Pact relates only to those problems which concern insular
                                possessions and insular dominions in the region of the Pacific.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Hughes</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>